{
  "response_text": "Average weekly whole milk consumption per agent begins at approximately 2,655 units and exhibits a sharp, monotonic decline during the initial phase, dropping to roughly 1,000 units by time step 10. This rapid decrease suggests that initial conditions and high incumbent habit strength were insufficient to prevent a widespread shift in consumption patterns early in the simulation. From time step 10 to 15, the rate of decline moderates, with consumption falling to approximately 900 units. During the intermediate phase, between time steps 15 and 27, the trend stabilizes into a slow, gradual descent, hovering between 850 and 600 units. Multiple statistical inflection points identified in this range indicate periods where the rate of change temporarily slowed or accelerated. Following time step 27, a second phase of accelerated decline commences, mirroring the steepness of the initial drop. Consumption falls sharply from roughly 600 units to a floor of approximately 300 units by time step 30. The data reaches its minimum observed value of 253 units at time step 32. This bifurcated decline pattern implies that consumers undergo distinct phases of behavioral adjustment, characterized by periods of rapid adoption of alternatives and periods of relative stagnation before a final transition to new norms."
}

